---
import Cite from './Cite.astro';
---

<section id="myth">
  <h2 class="section-title">THE TRUTH ABOUT "DOPAMINE DETOX"</h2>
  <p class="center">
    <span class="blink" style="color:#ff0000;font-size:20px;font-weight:bold"
      >★ MYTH BUSTED! ★</span
    >
  </p>

  <table class="retro-table">
    <caption>Fact vs. Fiction</caption>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>The Myth 🐍</th>
        <th>What's Actually True 🧠</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>
          You can "detox" or "reset" your dopamine by avoiding anything fun.
        </td>
        <td>
          Dopamine isn't a toxin and you can't flush it. Avoiding pleasure
          doesn't lower a baseline "level."<Cite source="cleveland" />
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>It's a brand-new biohacking trick from the internet.</td>
        <td>
          The term was coined by UCSF clinical professor <b>Dr. Cameron Sepah</b
          >, who meant a plain <b>cognitive-behavioral therapy</b> technique.<Cite
            source="wikiSepah"
          />
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>The more extreme the fast, the better it works.</td>
        <td>
          The real mechanism is <b>stimulus control</b>: remove the <i>cues</i> that
          start a compulsive habit so you don't run on willpower. Taken to a
          maladaptive extreme, it's just a fad.<Cite source="harvard" />
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="inset">
    <p style="margin:0">
      <b>Bottom line:</b> "dopamine detox" is a catchy, scientifically sloppy
      name for a real, boring, effective idea — <i
        >make the compulsive thing harder to reach.</i
      > That's the whole trick, and there's good evidence it works. 👇
    </p>
  </div>

  <hr class="rainbow-hr" />
</section>
